    "content": "In this season when many believers reflect on the sacrifice of Christ, Isaiah 53:5 stands as the clearest Old Testament declaration of substitutionary atonement. Every wound Jesus received was for someone else's sin. Every bruise was for someone else's rebellion. The chastisement that brought us peace fell upon Him, and by His stripes — the marks of the Roman whip — we are healed.\n\nThe word \"wounded\" in Hebrew is chalal, meaning pierced through or fatally wounded. This is not a superficial injury. It describes the nails driven through His hands and feet, the spear thrust into His side, the thorns pressed into His brow. Each wound was specific, deliberate, and substitutionary — endured not for His own sins, but for ours.\n\nThe concept of substitution is the heartbeat of the gospel. Someone else took your place. Someone else bore your punishment. Someone else absorbed the wrath that was directed at you. This is not a cold legal transaction — it is the most passionate act of love in the history of the universe. The Father gave His Son. The Son gave His life. And the Spirit applies the benefits to everyone who believes.\n\nThe chastisement of our peace was upon Him. Peace with God — shalom in its fullest sense — was purchased not by our efforts but by His suffering. The barrier between God and humanity was demolished not by human striving but by divine sacrifice. And the result is peace — real, deep, eternal peace with the Creator of the universe.\n\nToday, whatever wound you carry — physical, emotional, or spiritual — bring it to the One whose wounds purchased your healing. By His stripes, you are healed. Not you might be. Not you could be. You are healed. This is the finished work of the cross.",
