    "content": "In this season when many believers reflect on the passion of Christ, Psalm 22 takes us to a prophecy written a thousand years before the cross — yet so precise that it reads like an eyewitness account. David begins with the very words Jesus would cry from Golgotha: \"My God, my God, why hast thou forsaken me?\"\n\nThis is the most agonizing question ever uttered. On the cross, Jesus experienced something He had never known in all eternity: separation from the Father. Not because the Father stopped loving the Son, but because the Son was bearing the full weight of humanity's sin. In that moment, the sinless One became sin for us, and the holy God turned His face from the sin He cannot abide.\n\nPsalm 22 was not written by someone who had witnessed crucifixion — the practice did not exist in David's time. Yet David describes pierced hands and feet, bones out of joint, a heart melting like wax, and soldiers dividing garments by casting lots. Every detail was fulfilled in the crucifixion of Jesus, centuries after the psalm was composed.\n\nThe cry of abandonment is the price Jesus paid so that you would never have to be forsaken. He was abandoned so that you could be accepted. He was separated so that you could be united. He experienced the ultimate darkness so that you could walk in eternal light.\n\nToday, if you have ever felt forsaken or abandoned — by people, by circumstances, by life itself — know this: Jesus entered into that very experience on your behalf. He understands it. He has conquered it. And because He was forsaken for a moment, you are accepted forever.",
