    "content": "In this season when many believers reflect on the cross, the story of the Passover lamb reveals one of the most powerful foreshadowings of Christ's sacrifice in all of Scripture. On the night of Israel's deliverance from Egypt, God instructed each family to take an unblemished lamb, slaughter it, and apply its blood to the doorposts and lintels of their homes.\n\nThe blood was not decorative. It was protective. When the angel of death passed through Egypt, every home marked by the blood was spared. \"When I see the blood, I will pass over you.\" The judgment did not fall on the household that was covered by the blood of the lamb. This is the gospel in picture form — centuries before the cross.\n\nThe parallels to Christ are unmistakable. The lamb had to be without blemish, just as Christ was without sin. The lamb had to be slain, just as Christ gave His life on the cross. The blood had to be applied to the doorposts, just as the blood of Christ must be personally received by faith. Knowing about the lamb was not enough — the blood had to be applied.\n\nPaul makes the connection explicit in 1 Corinthians 5:7: \"For even Christ our Passover is sacrificed for us.\" Jesus is the fulfillment of every Passover lamb that was ever slain. His blood does not merely cover sin temporarily — it removes sin permanently. His sacrifice is not repeated annually — it was offered once for all time.\n\nToday, have you applied the blood? It is not enough to know about the sacrifice of Christ. You must personally receive it by faith. When God sees the blood of His Son covering your life, judgment passes over you. You are protected, redeemed, and free — not by your own merit, but by the blood of the Lamb.",
