    "scriptureText": "Then Pilate therefore took Jesus, and scourged him. And the soldiers platted a crown of thorns, and put it on his head, and they put on him a purple robe, And said, Hail, King of the Jews! and they smote him with their hands. Pilate therefore went forth again, and saith unto them, Behold, I bring him forth to you, that ye may know that I find no fault in him. Then came Jesus forth, wearing the crown of thorns, and the purple robe. And Pilate saith unto them, Behold the man!",
    "content": "In this season when many believers reflect on the passion of Christ, the scene before Pilate is one of the most tragic and triumphant moments in history. Pilate, the Roman governor, presented a scourged and bleeding Jesus to the crowd with two words: \"Behold the man!\" He intended it as an appeal for pity. But heaven intended it as a revelation of glory.\n\nThe scourging of Jesus was one of the most brutal forms of Roman punishment. The flagrum — a whip embedded with bone and metal — tore the flesh from the back of the prisoner, often exposing muscle and bone. Roman soldiers then twisted thorns into a crown and pressed it onto His head, mocking His claim to kingship. They dressed Him in a purple robe, placed a reed in His hand as a scepter, and bowed in mockery: \"Hail, King of the Jews!\"\n\nBut here is the profound irony: every act of mockery was, in fact, a coronation. The crown of thorns was a real crown. The purple robe was a real royal garment. The kneeling soldiers were performing an act of homage they did not understand. In their attempt to humiliate the King, they were actually enthroning Him. The cross itself would become His throne, and His suffering would become the source of His eternal reign.\n\nPilate declared, \"I find no fault in him.\" This is the legal verdict that establishes the innocence of the Lamb. The judge who sentenced Jesus publicly admitted there was no basis for the sentence. Jesus was not dying for His own crimes — He was dying for the crimes of the world.\n\nToday, behold the man. See the crown. See the blood. See the love that endured mockery, injustice, and agony without retaliating. This is the King who rules not by force but by sacrifice. This is the Savior who conquers not by war but by love.",
    "prayerPoints": [
      "Father, I behold the man — the scourged, crowned, mocked, and bleeding Savior — and I worship Him with everything in me.",
      "Lord Jesus, every act of mockery was a coronation. The crown of thorns is a real crown, and You are the real King.",
      "Holy Spirit, let the scene before Pilate break my heart afresh. The innocent was condemned so the guilty could go free.",
      "Father, Pilate found no fault in Jesus — yet He was sentenced to death. His innocence is my acquittal.",
      "Lord, help me to never grow numb to the cost of my salvation. Let the purple robe and the crown of thorns move me to deeper love."
    ],
    "faithDeclarations": [
      "I behold the man — crowned, scourged, and glorified in His suffering. He is the King whose throne is the cross.",
      "Every act of mockery was a coronation. The soldiers did not know it, but they were enthroning the King of kings.",
      "Pilate found no fault in Jesus. His innocence is my acquittal. His sentence is my freedom.",
      "The crown of thorns is a real crown. The purple robe is a real garment of royalty. Jesus is King — even in His suffering.",
      "My Savior conquers not by force but by sacrifice. His love is stronger than every weapon the world can wield.",
      "QUOTE: Pilate said behold the man. Heaven said behold the King. What the world sees as defeat, God sees as coronation.",
      "QUOTE: They mocked Him as a king and did not realize they were performing the most significant coronation in history.",
      "QUOTE: The thorns that pierced His brow were the curse of Genesis reversed. He wore our curse so we could wear His crown.",
      "PROPHETIC: I declare that the King who was crowned with thorns is now crowned with glory — and His reign is extending into every area of my life. The mockery of the enemy is being turned into the triumph of the King."
    ],
    "author": "Moses Afolabi",
