    "date": "2026-04-02",
    "title": "The Burial and the Borrowed Tomb",
    "scriptureReference": "Isaiah 53:9",
    "scriptureText": "And he made his grave with the wicked, and with the rich in his death; because he had done no violence, neither was any deceit in his mouth.",
    "content": "In this season when many believers reflect on the burial of Christ, Isaiah's prophecy provides another stunning detail fulfilled in Jesus: He would be assigned a grave with the wicked, yet be with the rich in His death. This seemingly contradictory prophecy was fulfilled when Jesus was crucified between two criminals — assigned a grave with the wicked — yet was buried in the tomb of Joseph of Arimathea, a wealthy man.\n\nThe burial of Jesus is often overlooked in our focus on the cross and the resurrection. But the burial matters. It confirms that Jesus truly died. This was not a fainting spell, a coma, or a near-death experience. The Son of God was dead. His body was wrapped in burial cloths, anointed with spices, and sealed in a rock-hewn tomb. The finality of death had claimed Him.\n\nJoseph of Arimathea, a secret disciple who was also a member of the Sanhedrin, came forward with courage after the crucifixion. He asked Pilate for the body of Jesus and placed it in his own new tomb. This act of devotion fulfilled Isaiah's prophecy and demonstrated that even in death, God was orchestrating every detail according to His Word.\n\nThe borrowed tomb also carries a beautiful symbolism: Jesus borrowed the tomb because He was not going to need it for long. He borrowed a donkey for His entry into Jerusalem. He borrowed an upper room for the Last Supper. And He borrowed a tomb for His burial. Everything He borrowed, He returned — better than He found it.\n\nToday, remember that the tomb is not the end of the story. It is the intermission between two acts: the sacrifice and the resurrection. The burial declares that the price was fully paid. But the empty tomb on the third day declares that death could not hold Him.",
