    "date": "2026-04-08",
    "title": "The Resurrection Body — What We Will Become",
    "scriptureReference": "1 Corinthians 15:42-44",
    "scriptureText": "So also is the resurrection of the dead. It is sown in corruption; it is raised in incorruption: It is sown in dishonour; it is raised in glory: it is sown in weakness; it is raised in power: It is sown a natural body; it is raised a spiritual body. There is a natural body, and there is a spiritual body.",
    "content": "In this season when many believers celebrate the resurrection of Christ, Paul reveals what the resurrection means for our own future: we too will be raised. And the body we receive will be radically, gloriously different from the one we now inhabit. What is sown in corruption will be raised in incorruption. What is sown in weakness will be raised in power.\n\nPaul uses the metaphor of sowing and reaping. A seed that is planted looks nothing like the plant that emerges. It is small, dry, and apparently lifeless. But when it is placed in the ground and covered with earth, something miraculous happens: life breaks forth. The seed dies, and from its death comes something far more glorious than the seed itself.\n\nThe contrasts Paul draws are breathtaking. Corruption versus incorruption — our current bodies decay, but our resurrection bodies will never deteriorate. Dishonor versus glory — our bodies are subject to weakness, illness, and aging, but they will be raised in radiant glory. Weakness versus power — the frailty of mortal flesh will give way to supernatural strength.\n\nThe final contrast is between a natural body and a spiritual body. The resurrection body is not less real than our current body — it is more real. Jesus' resurrection body could be touched, could eat food, and could be recognized. But it could also pass through locked doors and appear in different locations. It was physical, yet glorified — the perfect union of the material and the spiritual.\n\nToday, whatever limitations your physical body imposes — pain, illness, aging, disability — know that they are temporary. The resurrection promises a body that will never hurt, never age, never weaken, and never die. This is the hope of Easter. This is the promise of the risen Christ. And it is your inheritance.",
    "prayerPoints": [
      "Father, I thank You for the promise of a resurrection body — incorruptible, glorious, powerful, and eternal.",
      "Lord, let the hope of resurrection transform how I view physical limitations, illness, and aging. These are temporary — glory is forever.",
      "Holy Spirit, help me to live in light of the resurrection promise. What I sow in weakness today will be raised in power.",
      "Father, I grieve with those who suffer physically. Comfort them with the promise that their current body is not their final body.",
      "Lord, let the resurrection of Jesus be the guarantee of my own resurrection. Because He lives, I too shall live — in a glorified body."
    ],
