    "date": "2026-04-12",
    "title": "Steadfast and Immovable — Living in Resurrection Power",
    "scriptureReference": "1 Corinthians 15:58",
    "scriptureText": "Therefore, my beloved brethren, be ye stedfast, unmoveable, always abounding in the work of the Lord, forasmuch as ye know that your labour is not in vain in the Lord.",
    "content": "In this season when many believers celebrate the resurrection, Paul closes his magnificent chapter on the risen Christ with a practical charge: be steadfast, immovable, always abounding in the work of the Lord. The resurrection is not just a doctrine to believe — it is a power that produces action, endurance, and purpose.\n\nPaul has spent an entire chapter building the case for the resurrection. He has presented eyewitness testimony, theological arguments, and prophetic promises. And now he draws the conclusion: because the resurrection is real, your labor matters. It is not in vain. Every prayer, every sacrifice, every act of service, every moment of faithfulness — none of it is wasted.\n\nThe word \"steadfast\" means firmly established, not wavering. In a world of shifting opinions and unstable convictions, the resurrection gives you a foundation that cannot be shaken. Whatever cultural winds blow, whatever philosophical trends emerge, whatever personal trials arise — you can stand firm because you stand on the fact that Christ is risen.\n\n\"Immovable\" goes further. It does not mean rigid or inflexible — it means unable to be displaced from your position. You can be steadfast and still be pushed around. But immovable means nothing can knock you off your foundation. The resurrection makes you an immovable force in a world that tries to uproot everything.\n\n\"Always abounding in the work of the Lord\" is the natural overflow of resurrection confidence. When you know that your labor is not in vain, you work with energy, enthusiasm, and persistence. You do not burn out, because you are fueled by eternal significance, not temporal recognition. Today, be steadfast. Be immovable. Abound in the work of the Lord. And know that because of the resurrection, nothing you do for Christ is ever wasted.",
