    "date": "2026-05-04",
    "title": "Hannah's Prayer — A Mother's Faith That Changed a Nation",
    "scriptureReference": "1 Samuel 1:27-28",
    "scriptureText": "For this child I prayed; and the Lord hath given me my petition which I asked of him: Therefore also I have lent him to the Lord; as long as he liveth he shall be lent to the Lord. And he worshipped the Lord there.",
    "content": "While celebration dates vary across nations, the story of Hannah is a universal testimony of what happens when a mother pours out her heart before God. Hannah was barren, provoked by her rival, and deeply distressed. But she did not give up. She brought her anguish to the Lord and prayed with such intensity that the priest thought she was drunk.\n\nGod answered Hannah's prayer, and she gave birth to Samuel — the prophet who would anoint kings, guide a nation, and reshape the spiritual landscape of Israel. But Hannah's faith was not only demonstrated in her prayer. It was demonstrated in her surrender. She dedicated Samuel back to the Lord, fulfilling her vow and placing her most precious gift on the altar.\n\nThe phrase \"I have lent him to the Lord\" reveals a mother who understood that her children ultimately belong to God. She did not cling possessively to the answer to her prayer. She recognized that the same God who gave her Samuel had a purpose for him that was greater than her personal joy. True motherly love releases children into God's purposes.\n\nHannah's prayer of dedication in 1 Samuel 2 is one of the most theologically rich prayers in the Old Testament. It speaks of God's sovereignty, His justice, His power over life and death, and His exaltation of the humble. This is not the prayer of a simple woman — it is the prayer of a theologian, a prophet, and a worshipper. And she was a mother.\n\nToday, if you are a mother, know that your prayers carry extraordinary power. Hannah's prayer in a temple corridor produced a prophet who changed a nation. Your prayer in a quiet bedroom can produce results that will echo through generations. Never underestimate the power of a praying mother.",
