    "date": "2026-05-08",
    "title": "The Strength of a Virtuous Woman",
    "scriptureReference": "Proverbs 31:10-12",
    "scriptureText": "Who can find a virtuous woman? for her price is far above rubies. The heart of her husband doth safely trust in her, so that he shall have no need of spoil. She will do him good and not evil all the days of her life.",
    "content": "While celebration dates vary across nations, the portrait of the virtuous woman in Proverbs 31 continues to inspire and challenge every generation. The opening question — \"who can find a virtuous woman?\" — is not a statement of rarity in the sense of scarcity. It is a statement of value. Her worth is far above rubies — the most precious gemstones of the ancient world.\n\nThe Hebrew word for \"virtuous\" is chayil, which means strength, capability, and valor. This is not a fragile, passive woman. She is a woman of substance, skill, and spiritual power. The same word is used to describe mighty warriors in other parts of the Old Testament. The Proverbs 31 woman is a warrior in her own right — fighting for her family, her community, and her calling.\n\nThe trust placed in her by her husband is a testament to her character. He trusts her not because she is perfect, but because she is faithful. She is consistent, reliable, and committed to doing good — not occasionally, but \"all the days of her life.\" This is a lifetime commitment to integrity, love, and purpose.\n\nProverbs 31 is not a checklist for women to feel inadequate about. It is a celebration of what a Spirit-empowered woman can accomplish. She manages a household, runs a business, cares for the poor, speaks with wisdom, and does it all with strength and dignity. She is not defined by one role but by the character that infuses every role she occupies.\n\nToday, whether you are a mother, a grandmother, a wife, or a woman pursuing your calling, know that strength and virtue are your birthright in Christ. You are not called to be perfect — you are called to be faithful. And the woman who fears the Lord will be praised, not for her appearance, but for her character.",
