    "date": "2026-05-09",
    "title": "Honor Your Mother — A Command with Promise",
    "scriptureReference": "Exodus 20:12",
    "scriptureText": "Honour thy father and thy mother: that thy days may be long upon the land which the Lord thy God giveth thee.",
    "content": "While celebration dates vary across nations, God's command to honor mothers and fathers is universal and eternal. It is the fifth commandment — the first with a promise attached. Honoring parents is not merely a cultural tradition. It is a divine directive with spiritual consequences and tangible blessings.\n\nThe Hebrew word for \"honor\" is kavod, meaning to give weight, to regard as significant, to treat with gravity and respect. To honor your mother is to recognize the weight of her role, the significance of her sacrifice, and the value of her influence in your life. It is the opposite of dismissal, neglect, or ingratitude.\n\nPaul reinforces this command in Ephesians 6:2-3, calling it \"the first commandment with promise.\" The promise is long life — a quality of life that comes from living in alignment with God's order. When we honor the authorities God has placed in our lives, beginning with our parents, we position ourselves under the umbrella of divine blessing.\n\nHonoring your mother does not mean she was perfect. No mother is. But honor is not conditional on perfection — it is a response to the position God gave her in your life. Even when the relationship is complicated or painful, you can choose to honor the good, forgive the failures, and extend grace — just as God has extended grace to you.\n\nToday, find a way to honor your mother. If she is living, tell her you love her. If she is in heaven, thank God for her legacy. If your relationship is strained, begin with prayer and ask God for the grace to take one step toward reconciliation. Honoring your mother is not just a nice gesture — it is obedience to God with a promise attached.",
