    "date": "2026-05-26",
    "title": "Children Are a Heritage from the Lord",
    "scriptureReference": "Psalm 127:3-5",
    "scriptureText": "Lo, children are an heritage of the Lord: and the fruit of the womb is his reward. As arrows are in the hand of a mighty man; so are children of the youth. Happy is the man that hath his quiver full of them: they shall not be ashamed, but they shall speak with the enemies in the gate.",
    "content": "Children are not accidents, burdens, or afterthoughts. They are a heritage from the Lord — a divine inheritance entrusted to parents for a specific purpose. The psalmist compares children to arrows in the hand of a warrior, ready to be launched into the future with direction, power, and purpose.\n\nThe arrow metaphor is rich with meaning. An arrow does not choose its own direction — it is shaped, aimed, and released by the archer. Parents are the archers. Their responsibility is to shape the character of their children, aim them toward God's purposes, and release them at the right time with the right trajectory. Parenting is not possession — it is stewardship.\n\nThe phrase \"fruit of the womb is his reward\" declares that children are God's gift, not humanity's achievement. In a world that sometimes views children as inconveniences or commodities, Scripture elevates them to the status of divine reward. They are treasures entrusted to earthly stewards by a heavenly Father.\n\nThe promise that they shall \"speak with the enemies in the gate\" is significant. In the ancient Near East, the city gate was the place of legal proceedings, civic leadership, and community governance. Children who are well-raised become leaders who influence society, confront injustice, and represent their families with honor in the public square.\n\nToday, whether you are a parent, a grandparent, a teacher, or a mentor, recognize that every investment you make in a child is an investment in the future. The arrows you are shaping today will fly tomorrow — into communities, nations, and spheres of influence. Shape them with wisdom. Aim them with prayer. And release them with faith.",
