    "content": "The promise of Proverbs 22:6 has encouraged parents for millennia: train up a child in the way they should go, and when they are old, they will not depart from it. This is one of the most quoted verses on parenting in all of Scripture, and its wisdom is as relevant today as when Solomon penned it.\n\nThe Hebrew word for \"train up\" is chanak, which means to dedicate, to initiate, or to set a direction. It was used for the dedication of a new house or temple — the act of establishing its purpose from the beginning. Training a child is not merely behavior management. It is purpose establishment — setting the trajectory of a life from its earliest moments.\n\nThe phrase \"in the way he should go\" has been understood two ways: according to God's general path of righteousness, and according to the individual child's unique gifting and temperament. Both are valid. Good parenting involves teaching universal truths while simultaneously discerning and nurturing the unique design God has placed in each child.\n\nThe promise that they \"will not depart from it\" is a statement of principle, not an absolute guarantee that eliminates free will. Some children who are well-trained still go through seasons of wandering. But the training creates a spiritual compass that continues to point north, even during seasons of detour. The seeds planted in childhood have a way of sprouting in adulthood.\n\nToday, if you are raising children, take the long view. The training you provide may not produce immediate visible results. But the foundation you lay will endure. And if you are an adult who was trained in the way of the Lord as a child, know that those seeds are still alive, still active, and still pointing you home.",
