    "date": "2026-05-29",
    "title": "Protecting and Defending the Vulnerable",
    "scriptureReference": "Matthew 18:5-6",
    "scriptureText": "And whoso shall receive one such little child in my name receiveth me. But whoso shall offend one of these little ones which believe in me, it were better for him that a millstone were hanged about his neck, and that he were drowned in the depth of the sea.",
    "content": "Jesus' words about children are among the most protective and stern in all of Scripture. He declares that whoever receives a child in His name receives Him. And whoever causes harm to a child who believes in Him faces a consequence so severe that drowning would be preferable. God takes the protection of children seriously — and so must we.\n\nThe phrase \"receive one such little child in my name\" establishes that how we treat children is a direct reflection of how we treat Christ. When you welcome a child, care for a child, protect a child, or nurture a child — you are serving Jesus Himself. This elevates the care of children from a social responsibility to a sacred act of worship.\n\nThe warning about offending \"these little ones\" is one of the strongest judgments Jesus ever pronounced. The millstone He describes was not a small kitchen grindstone but a massive stone turned by a donkey — heavy enough to drag a grown man to the bottom of the sea. Jesus is saying that the judgment for harming a child is worse than the worst death imaginable.\n\nThis passage calls every believer, every church, and every community to be fierce defenders of children. In a world where children face exploitation, abuse, neglect, and poverty, the church must stand as a refuge, a shield, and a voice for the voiceless. This is not optional ministry — it is a non-negotiable mandate from the lips of Jesus Himself.\n\nToday, consider what you can do to protect, defend, and bless the children in your sphere of influence. Speak up for those who cannot speak for themselves. Create safe environments in your home, your church, and your community. And remember that in caring for the least of these, you are caring for Christ.",
