    "date": "2026-06-14",
    "title": "The Father Heart of God",
    "scriptureReference": "Psalm 68:5-6",
    "scriptureText": "A father of the fatherless, and a judge of the widows, is God in his holy habitation. God setteth the solitary in families: he bringeth out those which are bound with chains: but the rebellious dwell in a dry land.",
    "content": "While celebration dates vary across nations, the biblical call to honor fathers is rooted in the character of God Himself. He is the ultimate Father — the one from whom all fatherhood derives its meaning. And His heart is especially turned toward those who have no earthly father: He is \"a father of the fatherless.\"\n\nThis psalm reveals that God does not merely tolerate the fatherless — He actively seeks them out. He sets the solitary in families. He brings out those who are bound. He takes the isolated and places them in communities of belonging. The father heart of God is not passive. It is pursuing, providing, and protecting.\n\nEvery earthly father is a reflection — however imperfect — of the heavenly Father. When a father provides, he reflects God's provision. When a father protects, he reflects God's protection. When a father disciplines with love, he reflects God's discipline. And when a father is present, he reflects the most fundamental attribute of God: He is Emmanuel — God with us.\n\nBut the reality is that many fathers have fallen short. Some have been absent. Some have been harsh. Some have abandoned their responsibilities entirely. For those who carry the wounds of a broken or missing father, this truth is essential: God does not merely supplement what your earthly father failed to provide. He offers Himself as your true Father — the one who will never leave, never disappoint, and never fail.\n\nToday, whether you are a father, have a father, or long for the father you never had, turn your heart toward the one Father who is always faithful. He is the standard, the source, and the strength behind every good act of fatherhood on earth.",
