    "date": "2026-06-15",
    "title": "Fathers — Do Not Provoke, but Nurture",
    "scriptureReference": "Ephesians 6:4",
    "scriptureText": "And, ye fathers, provoke not your children to wrath: but bring them up in the nurture and admonition of the Lord.",
    "content": "While celebration dates vary across nations, Paul's instruction to fathers in Ephesians 6:4 speaks directly to the balance that godly fatherhood requires. On one hand, fathers must not provoke their children to anger. On the other, they must bring them up in the nurture and admonition of the Lord. This is the delicate art of fatherhood: strength tempered by tenderness.\n\nThe word \"provoke\" means to exasperate, to push beyond reasonable limits, to create frustration through harshness, favoritism, unreasonable demands, or emotional neglect. Fathers who provoke their children create deep wounds that can last a lifetime — wounds of rejection, inadequacy, and anger that often transfer into adult relationships with authority figures, including God Himself.\n\nPaul does not say fathers should avoid discipline. He says they should avoid provocation. There is a vast difference. Discipline that is consistent, loving, and purposeful builds character. Provocation that is harsh, inconsistent, or motivated by anger tears character down. The goal is not permissiveness — it is wisdom. Not indulgence — but grace-filled guidance.\n\nThe alternative to provocation is nurture — the Greek word paideia, which encompasses training, instruction, education, and discipline within a framework of love. This is the same word used for God's discipline of His children in Hebrews 12. It is not punishment for punishment's sake. It is purposeful formation designed to produce maturity.\n\nToday, if you are a father, examine your approach. Are you nurturing or provoking? Are you building your children up or tearing them down? The strongest fathers are not the loudest or the harshest — they are the ones who combine strength with gentleness, authority with affection, and discipline with unconditional love.",
