    "date": "2026-06-16",
    "title": "Abraham — The Father of Faith and Obedience",
    "scriptureReference": "Genesis 22:7-8",
    "scriptureText": "And Isaac spake unto Abraham his father, and said, My father: and he said, Here am I, my son. And he said, Behold the fire and the wood: but where is the lamb for a burnt offering? And Abraham said, My son, God will provide himself a lamb for a burnt offering: so they went both of them together.",
    "content": "While celebration dates vary across nations, the story of Abraham and Isaac on Mount Moriah stands as the ultimate picture of fatherly faith and obedience. When God asked Abraham to sacrifice his only son, Abraham faced the most agonizing test any father could endure. Yet his response reveals a faith so deep that it has inspired every generation since.\n\nThe dialogue between father and son is heartbreaking in its simplicity. Isaac asks the innocent question: \"Where is the lamb?\" He trusts his father so completely that he does not suspect anything. And Abraham's answer is one of the most prophetic statements in Scripture: \"God will provide himself a lamb.\" He was speaking more truth than he knew — for centuries later, God would indeed provide Himself as the Lamb on that very mountain range.\n\nAbraham's willingness to offer Isaac was not reckless faith. Hebrews 11:19 tells us that Abraham reasoned that God could raise the dead. He believed that even if Isaac died, God would bring him back. This is the logic of a father who has weighed the cost, counted the grief, and still trusted the character of God above his own understanding.\n\nThe fact that they \"went both of them together\" is one of the most moving phrases in Genesis. Father and son, walking side by side toward the altar, united in obedience. Isaac was old enough to resist — the wood for the sacrifice was on his back — yet he submitted to his father's leadership. This mutual trust between father and son is the model for every family.\n\nToday, the sacrifice of fatherhood requires laying down personal comfort, personal ambition, and personal preferences for the sake of the children God has entrusted to you. Like Abraham, faithful fathers trust God with their most precious gifts — and discover that God always provides.",
