    "date": "2026-06-20",
    "title": "Honor Your Father — Strength Through Respect",
    "scriptureReference": "Proverbs 23:22-25",
    "scriptureText": "Hearken unto thy father that begat thee, and despise not thy mother when she is old. Buy the truth, and sell it not; also wisdom, and instruction, and understanding. The father of the righteous shall greatly rejoice: and he that begetteth a wise child shall have joy of him. Thy father and thy mother shall be glad, and she that bare thee shall rejoice.",
    "content": "While celebration dates vary across nations, the call to honor fathers is woven throughout Scripture as a foundational principle of godly living. Solomon instructs: listen to your father who gave you life, and do not despise your mother when she is old. This is a call to lifelong honor — not just childhood obedience, but enduring respect that matures as you grow.\n\nThe phrase \"buy the truth, and sell it not\" is strategically placed in this passage about parental honor. The wisdom a father passes down — through instruction, correction, and example — is truth worth purchasing and never relinquishing. The values embedded in childhood are currency for a lifetime.\n\nSolomon then reveals the father's reward: \"The father of the righteous shall greatly rejoice.\" A father's deepest joy is not found in professional achievement, financial success, or social recognition. It is found in seeing his children walk in righteousness. Nothing brings a father more lasting joy than watching his children live with integrity, faith, and purpose.\n\nFor children, honoring your father is not always easy — especially when the relationship is complicated. But honor is not the same as agreement. You can honor someone whose decisions you disagree with. You can honor someone whose failures have caused you pain. Honor is a posture of the heart that chooses respect over resentment and gratitude over bitterness.\n\nToday, find a way to honor your father. If he is living, reach out with a word of appreciation. If he is no longer with you, thank God for the good he invested in your life. And if you are a father yourself, know that your greatest legacy is not what you build in your career — it is the righteousness you cultivate in your children.",
