    "title": "A Grateful Heart on the Day of Thanksgiving",
    "scriptureReference": "Psalm 107:1-3",
    "scriptureText": "O give thanks unto the Lord, for he is good: for his mercy endureth for ever. Let the redeemed of the Lord say so, whom he hath redeemed from the hand of the enemy; And gathered them out of the lands, from the east, and from the west, from the north, and from the south.",
    "content": "In seasons when many reflect on gratitude, Psalm 107 opens with a universal invitation: give thanks unto the Lord, for He is good. This is not a seasonal sentiment but an eternal truth. God's goodness is not cyclical — it is constant. His mercy does not expire — it endures forever. And those who have been redeemed should be the first to declare it.\n\nThe psalm calls on the redeemed to \"say so\" — to publicly declare the goodness of God. Gratitude that stays in the heart is incomplete. It must find expression through the mouth. When you tell someone what God has done for you, gratitude becomes testimony. And testimony has the power to strengthen the faith of others, challenge the skepticism of observers, and release fresh praise into the atmosphere.\n\nThe geographical sweep of verse 3 — from east and west, from north and south — declares that God's gathering of His people knows no borders. His redemption reaches every continent, every culture, and every language group. Gratitude is not a Western value or an Eastern tradition — it is a universal human response to a God whose goodness spans the entire earth.\n\nPsalm 107 goes on to describe four types of people whom God rescued: wanderers in the desert, prisoners in darkness, fools who suffered because of rebellion, and sailors caught in a storm. In each case, they cried out to the Lord, and He delivered them. And in each case, the response is the same: \"Oh that men would praise the Lord for his goodness, and for his wonderful works to the children of men!\"\n\nToday, let the redeemed of the Lord say so. Do not be silent about God's goodness. Do not take His mercy for granted. Open your mouth and give thanks — for He is good, His mercy endures forever, and His wonderful works deserve to be declared.",
