    "date": "2027-03-25",
    "title": "The Seven Last Words — Forgiveness from the Cross",
    "scriptureReference": "Luke 23:34",
    "scriptureText": "Then said Jesus, Father, forgive them; for they know not what they do. And they parted his raiment, and cast lots.",
    "content": "In this sacred season, the first of Jesus' seven statements from the cross is a prayer of forgiveness for His executioners: \"Father, forgive them; for they know not what they do.\" While nails were being driven through His hands and feet, while soldiers gambled for His clothing, while the crowd mocked and the religious leaders sneered — Jesus prayed for their forgiveness.\n\nThis prayer demolishes every excuse for unforgiveness. If Jesus could forgive those who were actively crucifying Him, no one can claim that their offender's actions are too severe to forgive. The cross is the ultimate standard of forgiveness — and it was offered in real time, in the midst of the pain, not after the wounds had healed.\n\n\"They know not what they do\" — Jesus attributes ignorance, not malice, to His executioners. The soldiers were following orders. The crowd was manipulated. Even the religious leaders, who acted with deliberate intent, did not fully comprehend that they were crucifying the Son of God. Jesus finds a way to extend grace even to those who deserve judgment. This is the radical nature of divine forgiveness.\n\nThe phrase \"Father, forgive them\" is intercessory. Jesus is not simply letting go of His own right to retaliation — He is actively asking the Father to release His executioners from the consequences of their actions. This is the highest form of forgiveness: not just refusing to hold a grudge, but actively seeking the blessing of those who have harmed you.\n\nToday, is there someone you need to forgive? Not because they deserve it — Jesus' executioners certainly did not — but because unforgiveness holds you captive, not the offender. The One who prayed for His murderers while dying on the cross empowers you to release those who have wronged you. Forgiveness is not a feeling — it is a decision, and the cross gives you the power to make it.",
