    "date": "2027-03-27",
    "title": "Good Friday — It Is Finished",
    "scriptureReference": "John 19:30",
    "scriptureText": "When Jesus therefore had received the vinegar, he said, It is finished: and he bowed his head, and gave up the ghost.",
    "content": "On this solemn day when many believers around the world commemorate the crucifixion of Jesus Christ, three words thunder across the centuries with finality: \"It is finished.\" In the Greek, it is a single word — tetelestai — a term used in commerce to mark a debt as \"paid in full.\" With this declaration, Jesus announced that the debt of human sin had been settled completely, permanently, and irrevocably.\n\n\"It is finished\" is not a cry of defeat. It is a shout of victory. Jesus did not say \"I am finished\" — as though He had been destroyed. He said \"It is finished\" — the work He came to do was completed. The mission was accomplished. Redemption was secured. The serpent's head was crushed. The curse of sin was broken. And the way back to the Father was opened forever.\n\nIn the moment of His death, the veil in the temple was torn from top to bottom — from top to bottom, not from bottom to top. This was not a human act. It was divine. The veil that separated the Holy of Holies from the rest of the temple — the barrier between God and humanity — was torn by God Himself. The access that only the high priest had once a year was now available to everyone, at all times, through the blood of Jesus.\n\n\"He bowed his head and gave up the ghost\" — the language is deliberate. Jesus was not killed. He gave up His life. He chose the moment of His death. He had the authority to lay His life down and the authority to take it up again. Even in death, He was sovereign. Even on the cross, He was King.\n\nToday, on this most sacred of days, rest in the truth that it is finished. Your sin debt is paid. Your access to God is open. Your future is secured. The work that Jesus accomplished on the cross needs nothing added to it. You cannot improve on \"finished.\" You can only receive it with gratitude and worship.",
