    "date": "2027-03-28",
    "title": "Resurrection Sunday — He Is Not Here, He Is Risen!",
    "scriptureReference": "Matthew 28:5-6",
    "scriptureText": "And the angel answered and said unto the women, Fear not ye: for I know that ye seek Jesus, which was crucified. He is not here: for he is risen, as he said. Come, see the place where the Lord lay.",
    "content": "Today, as many believers around the world celebrate the resurrection of Jesus Christ, the angel's declaration at the empty tomb is the most triumphant announcement in human history: \"He is not here: for he is risen!\" The stone is rolled away. The grave clothes are folded. The body is gone. And death — the final enemy, the unconquerable foe, the king of terrors — has been defeated.\n\nThe resurrection is not a metaphor for spiritual renewal. It is not a symbol of hope. It is a historical event — a physical body that was dead is now alive. The tomb is empty not because someone moved the body, but because the One who was dead got up and walked out. If the resurrection did not happen in literal, physical reality, then Christianity collapses. But if it did — and the evidence is overwhelming — then everything Jesus ever claimed is validated.\n\nThe angel's words contain a gentle rebuke: \"He is risen, as he said.\" Jesus had predicted His resurrection multiple times. He told His disciples He would be killed and rise on the third day. They heard Him say it. And still, they were surprised when it happened. The angel is reminding them — and us — that when God says something, He does it. Exactly as He said. Exactly when He said.\n\nThe invitation is remarkable: \"Come, see the place where the Lord lay.\" The angel does not ask them to believe blindly. He invites them to investigate. Come. See. Examine the evidence. The Christian faith is not afraid of examination — it welcomes it. The empty tomb stands as the most investigated site in ancient history, and it still proclaims: He is risen.\n\nToday, the resurrection changes everything. Death is defeated. Sin is conquered. Hope is alive. And the One who was dead is alive forevermore. This is not just history — this is your present reality. The risen Christ is alive, active, and reigning. And because He lives, you can face tomorrow.",
