    "date": "2027-03-29",
    "title": "The Road to Emmaus — Jesus Walks with the Brokenhearted",
    "scriptureReference": "Luke 24:15-16",
    "scriptureText": "And it came to pass, that, while they communed together and reasoned, Jesus himself drew near, and went with them. But their eyes were holden that they should not know him.",
    "content": "In this season of resurrection celebration, the road to Emmaus is one of the most tender post-resurrection encounters. Two disciples, devastated by the crucifixion, were walking away from Jerusalem — away from the community of believers, away from hope, and away from the empty tomb they had not yet understood. And Jesus Himself drew near and walked with them.\n\nThey did not recognize Him. Luke says \"their eyes were holden\" — restrained, held back from recognition. This was not an accident. Jesus intentionally concealed His identity so that He could walk with them in their confusion, listen to their grief, and teach them from the Scriptures before revealing Himself. He met them where they were, not where they should have been.\n\nAs they walked, Jesus opened the Scriptures to them, beginning from Moses and all the prophets, explaining everything concerning Himself. Their hearts burned within them as He spoke — that unmistakable warmth of divine truth piercing through grief and confusion. They were being healed through the Word before they even knew the Healer was walking beside them.\n\nIt was only at the breaking of bread that their eyes were opened. The moment Jesus broke bread — the same gesture from the Last Supper — they recognized Him. And immediately, He vanished. The recognition and the departure happened almost simultaneously, as if to teach them that His presence would no longer be limited to physical visibility. He would be present in the Word and in the breaking of bread.\n\nToday, Jesus still walks with the brokenhearted. He draws near when you are walking away from hope. He opens the Scriptures when your eyes are blinded by grief. And He reveals Himself in the breaking of bread — in communion, in fellowship, and in the ordinary moments when heaven suddenly becomes visible.",
