    "date": "2027-03-30",
    "title": "Thomas — Blessed Are Those Who Believe",
    "scriptureReference": "John 20:27-29",
    "scriptureText": "Then saith he to Thomas, Reach hither thy finger, and behold my hands; and reach hither thy hand, and thrust it into my side: and be not faithless, but believing. And Thomas answered and said unto him, My Lord and my God. Jesus saith unto him, Thomas, because thou hast seen me, thou hast believed: blessed are they that have not seen, and yet have believed.",
    "content": "In this season of resurrection celebration, the encounter between Jesus and Thomas is one of the most encouraging stories in the post-resurrection narrative. Thomas has been unfairly labeled \"Doubting Thomas\" for centuries, but his story is actually about the journey from honest doubt to the highest confession of faith in the New Testament: \"My Lord and my God.\"\n\nThomas was absent when Jesus first appeared to the disciples. When the others told him they had seen the risen Lord, Thomas declared he would not believe unless he could touch the nail marks and put his hand in Jesus' side. He was not being rebellious — he was being honest. His grief was too deep for secondhand testimony. He needed personal encounter.\n\nJesus did not reject Thomas for his doubt. Instead, He appeared specifically to address it. \"Reach hither thy finger, and behold my hands.\" Jesus met Thomas exactly where his doubt lived and provided the exact evidence he requested. He did not shame him. He did not lecture him. He extended His wounded hands and said: touch, and believe.\n\nThomas' response — \"My Lord and my God\" — is the highest christological confession in the Gospels. No other disciple in the four Gospels directly calls Jesus \"my God.\" Thomas moved from the deepest doubt to the highest faith. His journey proves that honest doubt, when brought to Jesus instead of away from Him, leads to the strongest conviction.\n\nToday, Jesus speaks to every doubter: \"Blessed are they that have not seen, and yet have believed.\" You have not touched the nail marks. You have not seen the empty tomb with your own eyes. But if you believe — if you take the testimony of Scripture and trust it — you receive a special blessing that Thomas himself did not have. Believing without seeing is not blind faith. It is the highest faith.",
