    "title": "The Ascension — Seated at the Right Hand of God",
    "scriptureReference": "Acts 1:9-11",
    "scriptureText": "And when he had spoken these things, while they beheld, he was taken up; and a cloud received him out of their sight. And while they looked stedfastly toward heaven as he went up, behold, two men stood by them in white apparel; Which also said, Ye men of Galilee, why stand ye gazing up into heaven? this same Jesus, which is taken up from you into heaven, shall so come in like manner as ye have seen him go into heaven.",
    "content": "In this season of resurrection celebration, the ascension of Jesus Christ is the event that completes the incarnation cycle: He came down from heaven, lived among us, died for us, rose from the dead, and returned to the Father — now seated at the right hand of God, possessing all authority in heaven and on earth.\n\nThe ascension is not a departure — it is a promotion. Jesus did not leave His disciples behind — He went ahead to prepare a place for them and to send the Holy Spirit in His place. His physical absence on earth is compensated by His spiritual omnipresence through the Spirit. He is closer to you now, through the Spirit, than He was to the disciples who walked beside Him.\n\nThe two men in white apparel — likely angels — asked a question that redirects the disciples' gaze: \"Why stand ye gazing up into heaven?\" The implication is clear: do not stand still. Do not merely look upward. There is work to do. The same Jesus who ascended will return — but between His going and His coming, there is a mission to fulfill, a gospel to preach, and a world to reach.\n\n\"This same Jesus shall so come in like manner\" — the promise of the Second Coming is embedded in the ascension. The way He left is the way He will return: visibly, physically, and in the clouds. The ascension is not the end of the Jesus story — it is the intermission. He will return, and when He does, every eye will see Him.\n\nToday, we live in the time between the ascension and the return. It is a time of mission, not of idle gazing. The risen Christ is seated at the right hand of the Father, interceding for you, ruling on your behalf, and preparing for the day when He will return to make all things new.",
