    "date": "2027-04-03",
    "title": "The Resurrection Body — What Awaits the Believer",
    "scriptureReference": "1 Corinthians 15:42-44",
    "scriptureText": "So also is the resurrection of the dead. It is sown in corruption; it is raised in incorruption: It is sown in dishonour; it is raised in glory: it is sown in weakness; it is raised in power: It is sown a natural body; it is raised a spiritual body. There is a natural body, and there is a spiritual body.",
    "content": "In this season of resurrection celebration, Paul describes the nature of the resurrection body that awaits every believer. Just as Christ was raised in a transformed, glorified body, so will those who belong to Him. The body that is buried in the ground is not the body that will be raised. What goes down is perishable. What comes up is eternal.\n\nPaul uses four contrasts to describe the transformation. Corruption becomes incorruption — what was subject to decay becomes permanently immune to it. Dishonor becomes glory — what was marked by shame is clothed in splendor. Weakness becomes power — what was frail and failing is infused with divine strength. Natural becomes spiritual — what was bound by physics is liberated by the Spirit.\n\nThe analogy of the seed is instructive: a seed planted in the ground looks nothing like the plant that emerges from it. An acorn bears no resemblance to the oak tree it produces. In the same way, the body that is buried bears no resemblance to the body that will be raised. The continuity is not in appearance — it is in identity. You will still be you, but perfected, glorified, and transformed.\n\nThe resurrection body of Jesus provides the prototype. He could be touched, He could eat, He spoke and was recognized — yet He could also pass through locked doors, appear and disappear, and ascend into heaven. The resurrection body is physical yet supernatural, recognizable yet transformed, real yet liberated from the limitations of the current physical world.\n\nToday, the resurrection is not just about what happened to Jesus two thousand years ago — it is about what will happen to you. If you belong to Christ, your body will be raised, transformed, and glorified. Death is not the end of your story. It is the transition between the seed and the oak tree, between the natural and the spiritual, between what is and what will be.",
